the video shows how the nematodes change the direction of the movement at the moment when they are exposed to sound impulses .
scientists put the worms with genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled by using ispuls sound waves .
tiny nematodes change the direction of the movement when they affect sound impulses , too high to the human ear can hear .
impulses influenced by activating neurons , genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves .
still on the topic : researchers manage brain activity with the help of light
scientists said that the worms are demonstrating the possibilities of a new technique called `` sonogenetics '' , the essence of which is to use ultrasound to initiate certain cells of the brain , heart and muscles , the ultrasound source is located outside of the body .
historical Analysis Chalasaṃuti , a researcher at the Salk Institute , La Jolla , California , told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure , in which a person is sent electrical impulses in the brain and that is used in the treatment of Parkinson 's disease .
worms nematodes usually do not react to ultrasound , but Chalasanya discovered that they started to react when they were placed in a fluid containing microscopic bubbles .
he discovered that the bubbles reinforce ultrasonic waves that penetrate into the body of the worms .
reinforced ultrasonic waves affect structures called `` ion channels TRP-4 '' found in the membranes of cells of worms .
ultrasonic waves make these ion channels open and excite the cells that are associated with them , according to a report in Nature Communications .
to create the nematodes that can be controlled through ultrasound , Chalasanya made genetic modifications of worms , so their motor neurons used ion channels TRP-4 .
during the use of ultrasound to influence the modified organisms sound waves reinforced microscopic bubbles and put into organisms worms , activating the modified motor neurons .
this technique is similar to that used in the `` optogenetics '' - a new direction that allows scientists to activate neurons using light pulses .
Chalasaṃa claims compared to this methodology sonogenetics may have some advantages .
unlike the light that is delivered to the target area of the brain by fiber optics , low-frequency ultrasound waves freely pass through the body 's tissue , so to deliver them does not need to pass inside cranial boxes .
`` We believe that for the treatment of certain neurological diseases in clinical conditions , the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to make human neurons sensitive to ultrasound signals , '' said Chalasaṃa .
he added that , in addition to this , the technique can be applied to muscular and insulin-producing cells .
